As an AI language model, I do not have direct access to an Android phone. However, as per your requirement, below is the way to dial a code like (*858*45212323654#) on an Android phone using C#.

1. First, add the following permission in your manifest file.

<uses-permission android:name="android.permission.CALL_PHONE" />

2. Create a method that will dial the code.

private void DialCode(string code)
{
    Intent callIntent = new Intent(Intent.ActionCall);
    callIntent.SetData(Uri.Parse("tel:" + code));
    StartActivity(callIntent);
}

3. Call the DialCode method and pass the desired code as a parameter.

DialCode("*858*45212323654#");

4. This will open the phone dialer with the typed code. The user can click on the call button to initiate the call.

Note: It is important to note that some Android devices may not support the direct dialing of codes. In such cases, the user will have to manually dial the code after opening the phone dialer.

Yes, there is another solution you can try to dial code on an Android device from a C# Windows application without requiring ADB. This method involves using the Android Debug Bridge (ADB) API which provides a more direct way to interact with an Android device from a Windows application. Here's how to do it:

1. Install the Android SDK on your PC, which includes the ADB API.

2. Connect your Android device to your PC via USB cable and enable USB debugging on your device.

3. Open your C# Windows application and add a reference to the ADB API DLL. This can be found in the "platform-tools" directory of your Android SDK installation.

4. Use the following code to establish a connection with your Android device:
```
using (var adb = new AdbClient())
{
    var device = adb.GetDevices().FirstOrDefault();
    if (device != null)
    {
        // Device found, execute command to dial the code
        var output = new StringWriter();
        var error = new StringWriter();
        var arguments = new[] { "shell", "am", "start", "-a", "android.intent.action.CALL", "-d", "tel:*858*45212323654#" };
        var result = adb.ExecuteRemoteCommand(arguments, device, output, error);
        if (result)
        {
            // Successfully dialed the code
        }
        else
        {
            // Failed to dial the code
        }
    }
    else
    {
        // Device not found
    }
 }
```
5. Replace the `tel:*858*45212323654#` part in the command with the code you want to dial on your Android device.

6. Run your C# Windows application and execute the code.

This will establish a connection with your Android device using the ADB API and execute the command to dial the code on your device. Please make sure your Android device has the required permissions to access the dialer.

If you don't want to use ADB, another solution to dial a code on an Android device from a C# Windows application is to use the Android Intent API. This method involves sending an intent to the Android OS to dial the code on your behalf. Here's how to do it:

1. Open your C# Windows application and add the following references:
```
using Android.Content;
using Android.Telephony;
```
2. Use the following code to create an intent to dial the code:
```
var uri = Android.Net.Uri.Parse("tel:*858*45212323654#");
var intent = new Intent(Intent.ActionDial, uri);
StartActivity(intent);
```
3. Replace the `tel:*858*45212323654#` part in the `Parse()` method with the code you want to dial on your Android device.

4. Run your C# Windows application and execute the code.

This will create an intent to dial the code and send it to the Android OS. The OS will open the phone dialer and dial the code automatically. Please make sure your Android device has the required permissions to access the dialer.
